## What It Is

An interactive single-page React app called "Hemp Gummies, Explained." It walks users through hemp-derived compounds (THC, CBD, CBN, CBG, etc.), dosing, product types, safety, legality, and includes an interactive gummy builder. Educational tone, not promotional.

## Repo

- GitHub: `coreyhall93/hemp-guide`
- Local: `~/hemp-guide`
- Live site: https://coreyhall93.github.io/hemp-guide/

## Tech Stack

- React 19 (single-component app)
- Vite 7 for build tooling
- Deployed to GitHub Pages via the `gh-pages` npm package
- No router, no CSS files, no external component libraries
- All styling is inline JS objects within the component
- Fonts: Geist and Geist Mono loaded from Google Fonts at runtime

## File Structure

```
~/hemp-guide/
├── index.html          # Minimal shell, resets, mounts #root
├── vite.config.js      # base: '/hemp-guide/' for GitHub Pages
├── package.json        # Vite + React + gh-pages
├── src/
│   ├── App.jsx         # The entire app (~430 lines, single component)
│   └── main.jsx        # Renders <App /> into #root
├── public/
│   └── vite.svg
└── .gitignore
```

## Key Details

- Everything lives in `src/App.jsx`. There are no other components, no separate CSS, no state management libraries. It's one file.
- The app uses `useState` and `useRef` from React. No other hooks or libraries.
- Sections are defined in a `SECS` array at the top of the file. Compound data lives in a `CMP` array. All content is hardcoded in the component.
- Inline styles use two font constants: `G` (Geist) and `GM` (Geist Mono), plus hex colors throughout.

## Deploying Changes

From `~/hemp-guide`:

```bash
npm run deploy
```

This runs `vite build` first (via the `predeploy` script), then pushes the `dist/` output to the `gh-pages` branch. The site updates within a minute or two.

Commit source changes to main separately:

```bash
git add -A
git commit -m "description of changes"
git push origin main
```

## Important

- The `base` in `vite.config.js` must stay as `/hemp-guide/` or all assets will 404 on GitHub Pages.
- The Google Fonts `<link>` tag is injected by the React component at runtime, not in `index.html`. If fonts break, add the link directly to `index.html`'s `<head>`.
